{"parse":{"title":"Little Wars","pageid":1822538,"revid":855564885,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p class=\"mw-empty-elt\">\n\n</p>\n<div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">For other uses, see <a href=\"/wiki/Little_Wars_(disambiguation)\" class=\"mw-disambig\" title=\"Little Wars (disambiguation)\">Little Wars (disambiguation)</a>.</div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:176px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Littlewars.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0d/Littlewars.jpg\" width=\"174\" height=\"222\" class=\"thumbimage\" data-file-width=\"174\" data-file-height=\"222\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Littlewars.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The cover of <i>Little Wars</i></div></div></div>\n<p><i><b>Little Wars</b></i> is a set of rules for playing with <a href=\"/wiki/Toy_soldier\" title=\"Toy soldier\">toy soldiers</a>, written by <a href=\"/wiki/H._G._Wells\" title=\"H. G. Wells\">H. G. Wells</a> in 1913. The book. which had a full title of  <i><b>Little Wars: a game for boys from twelve years of age to one hundred and fifty and for that more intelligent sort of girl who likes boys' games and books</b></i>, provided simple rules for <a href=\"/wiki/Miniature_wargaming\" title=\"Miniature wargaming\">Miniature wargaming</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Although first printed in 1913, an updated version was released in 2004.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Contents\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Contents</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Development\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Development</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Publication\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Publication</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Reception\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Reception</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Contents\">Contents</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Little_Wars&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Contents\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><i>Little Wars</i> included fairly simple rules for <a href=\"/wiki/Infantry\" title=\"Infantry\">infantry</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Cavalry\" title=\"Cavalry\">cavalry</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Artillery\" title=\"Artillery\">artillery</a> in the form of a toy <a href=\"/wiki/4.7_inch_gun\" title=\"4.7 inch gun\">4.7 inch gun</a> that launched projectiles, usually small wooden <a href=\"/wiki/Dowel\" title=\"Dowel\">dowels</a> to knock down enemy soldiers. In addition to its being a war game, the book hints at several philosophical aspects of <a href=\"/wiki/War\" title=\"War\">war</a>.\n</p><p>The book is written in a whimsical style and illustrated with amusing drawings and photographs of a game being played that Wells describes in the book. Wells also gives a description of the game from the view of one of the generals in the battle bombastically relating his memoirs.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Development\">Development</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Little_Wars&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Development\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:332px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:HG_Wells_playing_to_Little_Wars.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/HG_Wells_playing_to_Little_Wars.jpg/330px-HG_Wells_playing_to_Little_Wars.jpg\" width=\"330\" height=\"237\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/HG_Wells_playing_to_Little_Wars.jpg/495px-HG_Wells_playing_to_Little_Wars.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/HG_Wells_playing_to_Little_Wars.jpg/660px-HG_Wells_playing_to_Little_Wars.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1536\" data-file-height=\"1102\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:HG_Wells_playing_to_Little_Wars.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>H. G. Wells playing a wargame with <a href=\"/wiki/W._Britain\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"W. Britain\">W. Britain</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Toy_soldier\" title=\"Toy soldier\">toy soldiers</a> according to the rules of <i>Little Wars</i>.  Wells is using a piece of string cut to a set length of the distance his soldiers can move.  An <a href=\"/wiki/Umpire\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Umpire\">umpire</a> sits in a chair with his <a href=\"/wiki/Stopwatch\" title=\"Stopwatch\">stopwatch</a> timing Wells.  Wells' opponent waits for his turn to move and fire his cannon at Wells' soldiers.</div></div></div>\n<p>The development of the game is explained and Wells's thoughts on war, as he was known to be a <a href=\"/wiki/Pacifism\" title=\"Pacifism\">pacifist</a>, are revealed in his writing. According to Wells, the idea of the game developed from a visit by his friend <a href=\"/wiki/Jerome_K._Jerome\" title=\"Jerome K. Jerome\">Jerome K. Jerome</a>.  After dinner, Jerome began shooting down <a href=\"/wiki/Toy_soldier\" title=\"Toy soldier\">toy soldiers</a> with a toy cannon and Wells joined in to compete. The two decided that with an addition of written rules, a good <a href=\"/wiki/Kriegsspiel_(wargame)\" title=\"Kriegsspiel (wargame)\">Kriegsspiel</a> type game could be developed.  The game revolved around the use of lead <a href=\"/wiki/Permanent_mold_casting#Slush\" title=\"Permanent mold casting\">hollow cast</a> soldiers made by <a href=\"/wiki/Britains\" title=\"Britains\">W. Britain</a> and battlefields made from whatever materials were on hand, usually blocks or other toys. Simple rules of movement, firing, and <a href=\"/wiki/Close_combat\" title=\"Close combat\">close combat</a> were developed with a set amount of time for each player to move and fire. Wells also provides a chapter of \"Extensions and Amplifications of Little War\". In an appendix, Wells provides \"Little Wars and Kriegspiel\"; more complex rules to be played in a larger space involving <a href=\"/wiki/Military_logistics\" title=\"Military logistics\">military logistics</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Military_engineering\" title=\"Military engineering\">military engineers</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Charge_(warfare)#Cavalry_charges\" title=\"Charge (warfare)\">cavalry charges</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Military_railways\" title=\"Military railways\">railway transport of troops</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Publication\">Publication</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Little_Wars&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Publication\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><i>Little Wars</i> was first published in 1913 by Frank Palmer.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> <i>Little Wars</i> was republished in its unabridged form by <a href=\"/wiki/Da_Capo_Press\" title=\"Da Capo Press\">Da Capo Press</a> in 1977.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SG_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SG-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> There have been numerous other reprints and it is now available online at <a href=\"/wiki/Project_Gutenberg\" title=\"Project Gutenberg\">Project Gutenberg</a>, along with a previous game book by Wells called <i><a href=\"/wiki/Floor_Games\" title=\"Floor Games\">Floor Games</a></i> (1911). A 2004 edition of the book published by <a href=\"/wiki/Skirmisher_Publishing\" title=\"Skirmisher Publishing\">Skirmisher Publishing</a> includes an introduction by game designer <a href=\"/wiki/Michael_O._Varhola\" title=\"Michael O. Varhola\">Michael O. Varhola</a> and a foreword by <a href=\"/wiki/Gary_Gygax\" title=\"Gary Gygax\">Gary Gygax</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Reception\">Reception</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Little_Wars&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Reception\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>C. Ben Ostrander reviewed the 1977 unabridged version of <i>Little Wars</i> in <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Space_Gamer\" title=\"The Space Gamer\">The Space Gamer</a></i> No. 17.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SG_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SG-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Ostrander commented that \"There are many line drawings and photos of the author 'at play'. Although it is of little use to the modern gamer, this book stands as an interesting volume.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-SG_3-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SG-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Little_Wars&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Rundle, Michael (9 April 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/04/09/hg-wells-little-wars-how-_n_3044934.html\">\"How HG Wells Invented Modern War Games 100 Years Ago\"</a>. <i>The Huffington Post</i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Huffington+Post&amp;rft.atitle=How+HG+Wells+Invented+Modern+War+Games+100+Years+Ago&amp;rft.date=2013-04-09&amp;rft.aulast=Rundle&amp;rft.aufirst=Michael&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.huffingtonpost.co.uk%2F2013%2F04%2F09%2Fhg-wells-little-wars-how-_n_3044934.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALittle+Wars\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Palmer, Frank (16 Aug 1913). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/16th-august-1913/24/little-wars-by-h-g-wells-frank-palmer-2s-6d\">\"Little Wars. By H. G. Wells.\"</a> <i>The Spectator</i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Spectator&amp;rft.atitle=Little+Wars.+By+H.+G.+Wells.&amp;rft.date=1913-08-16&amp;rft.aulast=Palmer&amp;rft.aufirst=Frank&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farchive.spectator.co.uk%2Farticle%2F16th-august-1913%2F24%2Flittle-wars-by-h-g-wells-frank-palmer-2s-6d&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALittle+Wars\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-SG-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-SG_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-SG_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-SG_3-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Ostrander, C. Ben (May\u2013June 1978). \"Books\". <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Space_Gamer\" title=\"The Space Gamer\">The Space Gamer</a></i>. <a href=\"/wiki/Metagaming_Concepts\" title=\"Metagaming Concepts\">Metagaming</a> (17): 21.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Space+Gamer&amp;rft.atitle=Books&amp;rft.issue=17&amp;rft.pages=21&amp;rft.date=1978-05%2F1978-06&amp;rft.aulast=Ostrander&amp;rft.aufirst=C.+Ben&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALittle+Wars\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Little_Wars&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<table role=\"presentation\" class=\"mbox-small plainlinks sistersitebox\" style=\"background-color:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;color:#000\">\n<tbody><tr>\n<td class=\"mbox-image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/30px-Commons-logo.svg.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"40\" class=\"noviewer\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/45px-Commons-logo.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wi